Questions driving this analysis¶

Big questions from S&P:¶

  • How are users using the products

  • Recommend unseen web pages that are likely to be of value

More specific questions from S&P:¶

  • What general patterns do you observe in the data?
  • Do you observe any logical groupings of users? If so, how did you identify them?
  • Do you observe any logical groupings of pages? If so, how did you identify them?
  • Are there any pages or users you might choose to exclude from your analysis? If so, which ones and why?
  • One of our Product Managers would like to know which pages are most similar to page595 , Physical Survey. From the data, can you identify other highly related pages? How do you do so?
  • One of our Account Managers is planning a visit with user482. She would like to recommend a few pages to the user which they arent using yet, but might find interesting. From the data, can you identify new pages that are likely to be interesting to this particular user? How? Could this process be done for additional users in an automated way?
  • What documentation, references, and other resources did you use to help you with this challenge?

My goals in this exercise¶

My primary goals in this exercise are to deomonstrate that I understand the methods used to answer the central questions you've asked, that I can quickly teach myself the basics of those methods, that I can easily manipulate and clean data, and that I know when to stop. Solving the problems you've identified in this data science project could easily take up a year's worth of work, as could teaching myself more about the techniques I've employed. I'm stopping after having worked on this for a few days but at the point where.

Things I learned¶

Most of what I do in this notebook I taught myself in the last couple days (namely, network theory and recommendation engine theory using Surprise). Although I counsulted the internet extensively, I did not interactively consult with any other humans. I certainly haven't mastered the techniques I settled on, but I did get the basics down and hopefully have outlined where this work could go in the future.

Here are some of the specific things that I learned:

1. What web traffic data looks like.¶

This might be surprising given that it's 2018 but I've never actually worked with page view data before.

2. What page rank is and how to calculate¶

I've heard about the Google page rank algorithm, but I've never actually used it before. I learned that the page rank reflects the number of pages that link to a given page.

3. How to represent web traffic data as a network (graph)¶

I learned about how network data is structured, how to convert the page view data you sent me into a list of edges, and then how to display that as an actual directional network graph.

4. What recommendations engines are¶

I learned about the difference between content filtering and collaborative filtering. I recognized that content filtering would not work with this data (there may be some exceptions there since it might be possible to extract some latent features from the user and page view data, but I didn't explore this). Collaborative filtering calculates the similarity between users (user-user similarity) or items (item-item similarity). To do this you basically need to create a matrix with users as rows and items as columns and cells containing item ratings (or, in our case, page views or page rank).

5. How to create a user-item rating matrix¶

I was going to go down the "Let's build a recommendation engine by hand" rabbit hole, so I figured out how to create a user-item matrix with number of page views as the cell values. This turned out to be the wrong approach because I ultimately came across the Surprise library and found out that someone had done a lot of this work already.

6. How to use Surprise¶

Surprise lets you take a dataframe with the columns user, item, and rating, and basically does all the heavy lifting on the fly. Presumably this includes creating a user-item matrix on the fly and then computing measures of similiarity between either items or users.

Network graphing¶

This is the first big area of analysis that I explored. It occurred to me that the pages of your site are a big network and that to understand how users use your products, it might make sense to look at how they move about from page to page--i.e. how they traverse the nodes of a network. My analysis is rudimentary, I'm not yet completely sure how to interpret the findings, and there are some important modifications I need to make to the network data, but I think this is a promising avenue of inquiry.

I also computed the page rank of all the pages in your dataset, which I do know how to interpret and which is immediately informative. I do this using the networkx library's page_rank method, which computes some version of the eigenvector for each page.

Sort by userid and timestamp¶

The first thing I do is sort the dataframe of pageviews by userid and then by timestamp. This returns an approximation of user sessions.

Create list of edges (ordered pairs) in sequence¶

Network edges are represented as a list of ordered pairs of page views, e.g. in the tuple ('News', 'Article'), the user went from the News page to the Article page. The next tuple in the sequence might be ('Article', 'Report'). This is the data structure required by the networkx library.

In [27]:
# Create a list of edges, which are ordered pairs of page views

for idx, elem in enumerate(page_view_list): 
    thiselem = elem
    nextelem = page_view_list[(idx + 1) % len(page_view_list)]
    mytuple = (thiselem, nextelem)
    
    if thiselem != nextelem:
        page_view_edges.append(mytuple) # Excludes pages that refer back to themselves
In [32]:

Drawing a network graph¶

I'd never done this before so I was pretty excited when this worked. It took a little fiddling to find out how to make things pretty, and I'll admit this graph isn't actually all that useful yet. Each node is a page and there are lines connecting the page views, representing the sequence in which users traversed the page network. Since there are so many pages, I removed the labels from the nodes because they were impossible to read, but that would be useful at some point.

Building a simple recommendation engine¶

We want to use a collaborative filtering approach. Collaborative filtering calculates how similar two users are based on their vectors (of item ratings). A classic case is movie recommendations where users rate movies on a 1 to 5 star scale. We don't have ratings, but we do have page views and page rank.

Strategy 1¶

Since I've never actually done this before, my first strategy was to do it by hand. I created a user-page matrix and then was about the manually compute the cosine similarity of users/pages but then I realized there were easier ways to do this. However I'll leave this here for posterity.

# Make a helper method to get the top N page recommendations for each user
# (I lifted this directlyf from the Surprise documentation)

def get_top_n(predictions, n=10):
    '''Return the top-N recommendation for each user from a set of predictions.

    Args:
        predictions(list of Prediction objects): The list of predictions, as
            returned by the test method of an algorithm.
        n(int): The number of recommendation to output for each user. Default
            is 10.

    Returns:
    A dict where keys are user (raw) ids and values are lists of tuples:
        [(raw item id, rating estimation), ...] of size n.
    '''

    # First map the predictions to each user.
    top_n = defaultdict(list)
    for uid, iid, true_r, est, _ in predictions:
        top_n[uid].append((iid, est))

    # Then sort the predictions for each user and retrieve the k highest ones.
    for uid, user_ratings in top_n.items():
        user_ratings.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
        top_n[uid] = user_ratings[:n]

    return top_n
In [81]:
top_n = get_top_n(predictions, n=10)
top_n_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(top_n, orient='columns')

Predictions¶

What I've done is create a matrix that predicts the number of page views for each user for each page. The function I used to get the predictions returned a messy dictionary that I then converted to a slightly less messy data frame. Below you can see that each user is a column. Each cell contains both the recommended page and the predicted page view value. The first row contains the top prediction, and so on down to the 10th prediction (which is what I limited the model to predicting).

7                   (iCalendar, 34.9104924299)
8            (CEMS Unit Values, 33.6503860036)
9        (Maps - BB Map Branch, 33.2369172965)
Name: user482, dtype: object
Interpretation¶

The model compared the pages that every user visits and then found similar users by comparing the cosine similarity of the user-page-view vector (i.e. each row of a user-page matrix). Based on what those similar users liked, these are the predicted amount of times you would visit these pages.

Clearly there is still some work to do in terms of cleaning up the page data (e.g. we might want to remove the iCalendar page); however I left these all in for now because (a) short on time and (b) maybe you really care about whether people are using the iCal export feature.

As for automation, yes, there are a lot of ways you could automate this process. The basic idea would be to automate the model execution and the process of sending the recommendations (model outputs) to a user (e.g. have them pop up on the user's landing page or email the top recommendations to them every month).

Pages similar to page595¶

"One of our Product Managers would like to know which pages are most similar to page595 , Physical Survey. From the data, can you identify other highly related pages? How do you do so?"

How I would answer this question:¶

What you'd want to do is calculate the cosine similarity (or Pearson or Mean Squared Difference) of the vectors of all the pages and then look at how similar page595 is to other pages. I haven't figured out how to do this manually yet, but there are ways to do it with Surprise.
